Professor Martha Collin is a historian with a special interest in medieval cookery.

40
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Here, she explains to BBC World Service Program the Food Chain, while long-lasting foods could have been familiar to people in the Middle Ages.

41
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:56.000
In theory, it would make sense to think that people who didn't have matches or fire starters, for whom starting a fire from scratch was quite a cumbersome process,

42
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:07.000
would naturally want to keep a stew pot bubbling if they had the means to do that and to avoid the labor of constantly restarting the fire.

43
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And also to make sure that they had a hot meal waiting at any time.

44
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Having hot food bubbling away on the fire means there is always something ready to eat, and a void having to start a fire from scratch.

45
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:30.000
When you do something like cook food or make a fire from scratch, you do it from the beginning, without the help of anything that has already been made.

46
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Starting a fire is also cumbersome, an adjective meaning difficult to do, taking time and effort.

47
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:45.000
